text: Edh demand is a bit of a keynesian beauty contest
I called inexorable tide as a spec when atraxa got spoiled and had a ton of 60 card users tell me I was an idiot peddling bad cards
When in reality, popularity is so much more important than how good or efficient a card is
the more a card can be named off the top of collective's people head, the better the card will sell
I assume that the bump on Sundays correspond to when stores often run edh leagues?
actually i think its the opposite
i think people visit the site less when they are playing, hence the dip on fridays and saturdays
also the actual days of the prereleases my traffic goes down
my current theory is people check the website a little bit going into the weekend, then sunday have all these ideas they want to check out
Seems legit.
I was thinking of the downtime people have between rounds in a league, wandering in front of the card cases, and trying to remember what they should get for their next deck idea.
But I'm a brewer, and that's probably just brewer mentality on my part.  :slightly_smiling_face:
It makes sense that most casuals are playing Fri and Sat evenings with their personal group, and Sun they're looking for the tools to do better next time.
I think, on average at least, that people are least likely to be working on sundays
I wonder if there is seasonality in there as well
Like in the finance world there is that well-known december slump when people stop spending money on cards until after christmas
There are the obvious events like set releases, but we know game knights influences things
I imagine Mitch's budget stuff moves the needle
i do have seasonality in traffic
i see a dip in the holidays like december, then see an uptick in january
summer dips a bit but in 2018 i think the dip turned into a pleateau due to overall growth
